    "### 4.8.2 Encoding Strategy Selection\n",
    "\n",
    "| Feature | Type | Unique Values | Encoding | Reasoning |\n",
    "|---|---|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Gender | Nominal | 2 (Male, Female) | One-Hot | No natural order between genders — one-hot avoids implying a ranking. Low cardinality (2 values) means only 1 extra column after dropping one dummy. |\n",
    "| CampaignChannel | Nominal | 4 (Email, PPC, Referral, Social Media) | One-Hot | Channels have no inherent order — label encoding would falsely imply PPC > Email or similar. 4 values keeps dimensionality manageable. |\n",
    "| CampaignType | Nominal | 3 (Awareness, Conversion, Retention) | One-Hot | Although there is a loose funnel logic (awareness → conversion → retention), these are distinct strategies, not a ranked scale. One-hot is safer than imposing an ordinal assumption the model may exploit incorrectly. |\n",
    "| AdvertisingPlatform | Constant | 1 (IsConfid) | Drop | Single value — zero information gain. Already flagged for removal. |\n",
    "| AdvertisingTool | Constant | 1 (ToolConfid) | Drop | Same as above. |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why One-Hot for all three?** All categorical features are nominal with low cardinality (2–4 values). One-hot encoding is the safest choice because it does not impose any false ordinal relationship. With only 3 features producing a maximum of 9 dummy columns (or 6 after dropping one level per feature to avoid multicollinearity), dimensionality is not a concern.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why not Target Encoding?** Target encoding replaces categories with the mean of the target variable per category. While effective for high-cardinality features, it risks data leakage if not applied strictly within cross-validation folds. Our features have at most 4 categories — one-hot is simpler, leakage-free, and equally effective at this scale."
   ]
