    "## 4.9 Feature Scaling and Normalization\n",
    "\n",
    "Algorithms like Logistic Regression, SVM, and KNN rely on distance or gradient calculations — if features vary widely in scale, a single high-magnitude column like Income (range: ~20k–150k) will dominate over ClickThroughRate (range: 0–1). Tree-based models like Random Forest and XGBoost are not scale-sensitive.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Scaler | Use When | Effect |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| StandardScaler | Data is roughly normal | Transforms to mean=0, std=1 |\n",
    "| MinMaxScaler | You want a fixed 0–1 range | Preserves shape but exaggerates outliers |\n",
    "| RobustScaler | Data contains outliers | Uses median and IQR — stable with extremes |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Our choice: RobustScaler** — because the outlier analysis in Section 4.7 confirmed genuine extremes in Income, AdSpend, and LoyaltyPoints. RobustScaler handles these without distortion. We will apply it only to the Logistic Regression pipeline; tree-based models will receive unscaled data.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.9.1 Identify Numerical Features and Scale Ranges Before Scaling"
   ]
