    "## 4.12 Handling Class Imbalance\n",
    "\n",
    "Class imbalance occurs when one class is much rarer than the other. If left unaddressed, the model may learn to ignore the minority class entirely — achieving high accuracy by always predicting the majority class while missing the cases that actually matter.\n",
    "\n",
    "Resampling must only be applied to the training set — never to validation or test — to avoid data leakage.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Strategy | What It Does | When to Use |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Undersampling | Removes majority class examples | Large datasets where losing data is acceptable |\n",
    "| Oversampling | Duplicates minority class examples | Quick fix, but risks overfitting |\n",
    "| SMOTE | Generates synthetic minority samples via interpolation | Minority class too small for simple duplication |\n",
    "| Combined (SMOTEENN) | SMOTE + cleaning noisy samples | Imbalanced and noisy data |\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.12.1 Assess Current Class Distribution"
